Here are the five .NET 10 breaking changes you're hitting and what to fix:

**1. InlineArray + explicit StructLayout Size**
.NET 10 disallows combining `[InlineArray]` with `[StructLayout(Size=…)]`. Remove the explicit size — the runtime now computes it from the element type and length.

```csharp
// Before (breaks in .NET 10)
[InlineArray(16)]
[StructLayout(LayoutKind.Explicit, Size = 64)]
struct MyBuffer { ... }

// After
[InlineArray(16)]
struct MyBuffer
{
    private int _element0;
}
```

**2. DriveInfo.DriveFormat on Linux**
On Linux, `DriveFormat` now returns the real filesystem type (e.g., `"ext4"`, `"xfs"`, `"btrfs"`) instead of the previous less-reliable value. Update any string comparisons to use the actual filesystem type names.

**3. NU1510 — dependency pruning warnings**
.NET 10 restore now prunes unused transitive framework references, emitting NU1510. If the warnings are noise, suppress them in your project file:

```xml
<PropertyGroup>
  <SuppressDependencyPruning>true</SuppressDependencyPruning>
</PropertyGroup>
```

Or suppress just the warning: `<NoWarn>$(NoWarn);NU1510</NoWarn>`. Ideally, verify the pruned references are truly unused first.

**4. NuGet audit now covers transitive dependencies**
`NuGetAuditMode` defaults to `all` in .NET 10 (was `direct`). You'll now get vulnerability warnings for transitive packages. Run `dotnet restore` and address any new `NU1901`–`NU1904` warnings by updating vulnerable transitive packages or pinning safe versions.

**5. FilePatternMatch.Stem is now non-nullable**
`Stem` changed from `string?` to `string` (returns `string.Empty` instead of `null`). Replace null checks:

```csharp
// Before
if (match.Stem is null) { ... }

// After
if (match.Stem.Length == 0) { ... }
// or
if (match.Stem == string.Empty) { ... }
```
